The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
Toe resembles the back of a prehistoric saurian, the stairway to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname Maison en oss.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, here is all that is ypic for Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The frontal façade of the house runs its dream lines, its pleasant colours and textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of shine of the colors is reinforced.
The coiling and torsion of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood horizontally copies windows, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, eyeballs and slabs.
The house Battlo, which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia on the number. 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, initially insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new one, but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and better market reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-family home was not thought of by Gaudi alone.
architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for an apartment of representation of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the façade.
For the facade have also worked with other artists and creators.
The joint work for the Casa Battlo house plans began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park, where there are other works by Gaudi.
The premises named the house hot just after its finishing due to its organic forms "the House of Bones".
Others, in view of the specific window opening mechanism, called it "the house that leases".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint Georges the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with vents of ventilation and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree inclination seems strange.
In the course of Gaudi's creation, the construction guidelines were absolutely not complied with and were not hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permit to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the municipal council was horrified and asked for modifications.
It was not, for example, pleasant for the members of the municipal council that the pillars of construction were embroidered on the public side.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the appeal of the city Josep Battlo asked (and was satisfied) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is divided by a staircase that accesses to an independent toe terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space liaison.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the high-ranking society can communicate comfortably or restrict itself to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has also received new facades a non-traditional weed and two floors in addition.
The game of Gaudi with the light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with the light wells.
The double-colored game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was only enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark which, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
Casa Battlo House, which was listed in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found that it was a lucrative company and they extended the field of visits to common areas and at the grind including toe terraces.
The ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price in the other buildings of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
