Devices to track people are increasingly being demanded by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear of their children is driving more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, put in place at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as exemplified by the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be of the size of a watch.
The case of the little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to seek ways to better protect their children.
Even though the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage, but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of a person who is not aware of them, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are clients who actually buy the product for safety reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes the "box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control."
"The mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
In her view, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly questionable.
"In the case of a prepared rapt, the author will do everything possible to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As the tracking devices develop, they (the criminals) will also seek them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases, criminals will always be ahead of the police," said the psychologist.
It nevertheless admits that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the RC Monitoring Company, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, saying that having such a device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The apparatus may be set up in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a specified period of time".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned shall remain."
'The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slided and finds himself in an extended position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special software program.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to that used in pendants of the size of a lighter box or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Well, he'll figure it out after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as tracking cars.
This is a combination of GPS-based position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in self navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
