A longer index than the calendar is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with a longer index than their ring are less likely to have prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years," announced the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index shorter than the calendar.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
However, in the case of those who had the index longer than the calendar the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years the risk reduction was 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - includes different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that testosterone helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but that he does not seem to have "complete evidence" of the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer.
