Can civility bring the cleavage closer?
After a campaign marked by invectiveness and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a preliminary sign of genuine bipartite cooperation towards the front or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not lead to any breakthroughs on the major issues to be addressed during the session of the "boiled duck".
But obviously there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties and the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to mark points.
The public meeting of the Committee on the President's deficit on Wednesday was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a period of trial and mutual testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limitations of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
Therefore, the Tuesday meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether tax, expenditure, health care or rights, both sides remain at miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed on tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Ethics and Public Policy Centre.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
The elections spark partisan passions and then they disappear.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the session of "bad ducks", Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a part or the whole, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After the meeting of Tuesday at the White House, more optimism is planned on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "bad duck", with the ratification of the "NewSTART" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely or even inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done will, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I see most of what is happening between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacle or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and to the tea voters who contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to meet their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial responses to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing some taxes, raising retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their opinion, have imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they needed 14 votes in committee, consisting of 18 members, to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they had difficulty reaching that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there are few reasons or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the struggles between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as the Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the spirit of support for the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the public.
Those who are judged to be in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
However, this would be an optimistic point of view.
Partisan spirit and polarization are larger today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at that time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties saw 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
In view of this reality, this week's civility could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will need to be made by both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
