2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely penalised, they may be obliged to declare themselves in cessation of payments, and in that case the private sector will also bear a portion of the costs.
Germany tells us that we need to follow a strong growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be bad not to hear it.
It is not just a question of renewing the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked for is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring greater peace to us.
And that we can grasp the opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with the big companies and the announcement of yesterday's new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticisms, the way has been opened for the thesis that order must be put at home.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to move it.
And one of the opportunities envisaged cannot be ruled out from abandoning a too bleak monetary zone in less serious countries.
