The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People must go to Service Centres for Visa Applicants prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing process at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to come to Service Centres for Visa Applicants (ASC, according to its stamps in English) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will receive biometric information from the applicant, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for the aspirants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with a request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for commercial and investor visas.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to present themselves to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves to the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and they will receive their marks.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra 26-dollar service fee.
For more information on the new procedure to apply for the visa, visit the following page: http://mexico.usembssy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
