A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries for a greenhouse gas reduction (GHG) that is almost one third of the additional reduction required to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to make in Cancún in order to compensate for the lack of binding commitments by industrialized countries to reduce them.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), most of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of global car park emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that would increase overall GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But this balance sheet will have to be subtracted from 5 Gt to stabilize by 2020 the increase in the climate at 2 degrees centigrades to avoid it becoming out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the remainder, i.e. 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the need for energy is reduced by twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company also participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have posted reserves of fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and they need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce wasted electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country will make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and $8 million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants costing $2.5 billion in construction.
