The rule that secret files should be composed only of already known news is essential to the dynamics of secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templiers or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous books.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (don't know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who reassert what they had already learned.
It's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) the chief of secret services (if not, as I know, editor of Liberation), who holds only as true as he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the Department of State was the same as that that Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the disclosures on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what any cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for a few small representation exercises, have become spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy under the wrong light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country is taking a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal doesn't put both the victims and the "strikes" in crisis.
But let us come to the deep nature of what has happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved to be complete since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the motorway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eyes of power.
But when one shows, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control ratio ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's revenge - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel said already, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true, that all knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it is within the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to remove all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future the States will no longer be able to publish any reserved information - this would be to publish it on a sticky poster at the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is vain to be able to maintain confidential telephone relations.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved in and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know well that, for the moment, my prediction falls within the realm of science fiction and is, therefore, romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence on uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in closed drawers with key: in the bottom, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving into crab, that is to say, backwards.
