Climate: how France embarrasses its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the promises of rapidly released financing (fast start or early funding) made by the developed countries.
And the big French dolls are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU came out of the big game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large-scale event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has raised EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which sets it on track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at things in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be "new and additional", according to the Copenhagen agreement, in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained and it adds 150 million over three years for fast-start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" for 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditures from previous years or at the overall level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution of grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each one chooses his or her method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that a loan of €1 is equal to a given one.
Of course, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to mitigation based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given ... At the most, should be counted on its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France only has such a reasoning: it 'respects' its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document for verification by yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (otherwise) respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-by!
In summary, France, in its fast-start financing, is operating a double scam: on the one hand, the evolution of action over time and on the other, the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it can suggest that it spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that Bercy has achieved arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (Why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in negotiations since developing countries are not completely tired...
Early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to the whole climate discussion.
But it could be an additional sand grain in the huge UNFCCC machine.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its method of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward discussions on long-term financing issues (other crucial chapter being discussed at the moment): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of recording loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Therefore, hope rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
